01217 /**
01218  * cvmx_agl_gmx_bad_reg
01219  *
01220  * AGL_GMX_BAD_REG = A collection of things that have gone very, very wrong
01221  *
01222  *
01223  * Notes:
01224  * OUT_OVR[0], LOSTSTAT[0], OVRFLW, TXPOP, TXPSH    will be reset when MIX0_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
01225  * OUT_OVR[1], LOSTSTAT[1], OVRFLW1, TXPOP1, TXPSH1 will be reset when MIX1_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
01226  * STATOVR will be reset when both MIX0/1_CTL[RESET] are set to 1.
01227  */
01228 union cvmx_agl_gmx_bad_reg {
01229     uint64_t u64;
01230     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_bad_reg_s {
01231 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01232     uint64_t reserved_38_63               : 26;
01233     uint64_t txpsh1                       : 1;  /**< TX FIFO overflow (MII1) */
01234     uint64_t txpop1                       : 1;  /**< TX FIFO underflow (MII1) */
01235     uint64_t ovrflw1                      : 1;  /**< RX FIFO overflow (MII1) */
01236     uint64_t txpsh                        : 1;  /**< TX FIFO overflow (RGMII0) */
01237     uint64_t txpop                        : 1;  /**< TX FIFO underflow (RGMII0) */
01238     uint64_t ovrflw                       : 1;  /**< RX FIFO overflow (RGMII0) */
01239     uint64_t reserved_27_31               : 5;
01240     uint64_t statovr                      : 1;  /**< TX Statistics overflow */
01241     uint64_t reserved_24_25               : 2;
01242     uint64_t loststat                     : 2;  /**< TX Statistics data was over-written
01243                                                          In RGMII, one bit per port
01244                                                          TX Stats are corrupted */
01245     uint64_t reserved_4_21                : 18;
01246     uint64_t out_ovr                      : 2;  /**< Outbound data FIFO overflow */
01247     uint64_t reserved_0_1                 : 2;
01248 #else
01249     uint64_t reserved_0_1                 : 2;
01250     uint64_t out_ovr                      : 2;
01251     uint64_t reserved_4_21                : 18;
01252     uint64_t loststat                     : 2;
01253     uint64_t reserved_24_25               : 2;
01254     uint64_t statovr                      : 1;
01255     uint64_t reserved_27_31               : 5;
01256     uint64_t ovrflw                       : 1;
01257     uint64_t txpop                        : 1;
01258     uint64_t txpsh                        : 1;
01259     uint64_t ovrflw1                      : 1;
01260     uint64_t txpop1                       : 1;
01261     uint64_t txpsh1                       : 1;
01262     uint64_t reserved_38_63               : 26;
01263 #endif
01264     } s;
01265     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_bad_reg_cn52xx {
01266 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

01268     uint64_t txpsh1                       : 1;  /**< TX FIFO overflow (MII1) */

01270     uint64_t ovrflw1                      : 1;  /**< RX FIFO overflow (MII1) */
01271     uint64_t txpsh                        : 1;  /**< TX FIFO overflow (MII0) */
01272     uint64_t txpop                        : 1;  /**< TX FIFO underflow (MII0) */

01275     uint64_t statovr                      : 1;  /**< TX Statistics overflow */

01277     uint64_t loststat                     : 1;  /**< TX Statistics data was over-written
01278                                                          TX Stats are corrupted */

01294     uint64_t txpop1                       : 1;

01540                                                          Only valid for 1000Mbs half-duplex operation
01541                                                          0 = burst length of 0x2000 (halfdup / 1000Mbs)
01542                                                          1 = burst length of 0x0    (all other modes) */
01543     uint64_t tx_en                        : 1;  /**< Port enable.  Must be set for Octane to send
01544                                                          RMGII traffic.   When this bit clear on a given
01545                                                          port, then all packet cycles will appear as

01548                                                          RMGII traffic.  When this bit clear on a given
01549                                                          port, then the all packet cycles will appear as
01550                                                          inter-frame cycles. */

01552                                                          0 = 512 bitimes (10/100Mbs operation)
01553                                                          1 = 4096 bitimes (1000Mbs operation) */
01554     uint64_t duplex                       : 1;  /**< Duplex
01555                                                          0 = Half Duplex (collisions/extentions/bursts)
01556                                                          1 = Full Duplex */
01557     uint64_t speed                        : 1;  /**< Link Speed LSB [SPEED_MSB:SPEED]
01558                                                          10 = 10Mbs operation
01559                                                          00 = 100Mbs operation
01560                                                          01 = 1000Mbs operation
01561                                                          11 = Reserved */
01562     uint64_t en                           : 1;  /**< Link Enable
01563                                                          When EN is clear, packets will not be received
01564                                                          or transmitted (including PAUSE and JAM packets).
01565                                                          If EN is cleared while a packet is currently
01566                                                          being received or transmitted, the packet will
01567                                                          be allowed to complete before the bus is idled.
01568                                                          On the RX side, subsequent packets in a burst
01569                                                          will be ignored. */
01570 #else

01572     uint64_t speed                        : 1;

01574     uint64_t slottime                     : 1;

01583     uint64_t reserved_14_63               : 50;
01584 #endif

01872 /**
01873  * cvmx_agl_gmx_rx#_adr_ctl
01874  *
01875  * AGL_GMX_RX_ADR_CTL = Address Filtering Control
01876  *
01877  *
01878  * Notes:
01879  * * ALGORITHM
01880  *   Here is some pseudo code that represents the address filter behavior.
01881  *
01882  *      @verbatim
01883  *      bool dmac_addr_filter(uint8 prt, uint48 dmac) [
01884  *        ASSERT(prt >= 0 && prt <= 3);
01885  *        if (is_bcst(dmac))                               // broadcast accept
01886  *          return (AGL_GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CTL[BCST] ? ACCEPT : REJECT);
01887  *        if (is_mcst(dmac) & AGL_GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CTL[MCST] == 1)   // multicast reject
01888  *          return REJECT;
01889  *        if (is_mcst(dmac) & AGL_GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CTL[MCST] == 2)   // multicast accept
01890  *          return ACCEPT;
01891  *
01892  *        cam_hit = 0;
01893  *
01894  *        for (i=0; i<8; i++) [
01895  *          if (AGL_GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CAM_EN[EN<i>] == 0)
01896  *            continue;
01897  *          uint48 unswizzled_mac_adr = 0x0;
01898  *          for (j=5; j>=0; j--) [
01899  *             unswizzled_mac_adr = (unswizzled_mac_adr << 8) | AGL_GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CAM[j][ADR<i*8+7:i*8>];
01900  *          ]
01901  *          if (unswizzled_mac_adr == dmac) [
01902  *            cam_hit = 1;
01903  *            break;
01904  *          ]
01905  *        ]
01906  *
01907  *        if (cam_hit)
01908  *          return (AGL_GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CTL[CAM_MODE] ? ACCEPT : REJECT);
01909  *        else
01910  *          return (AGL_GMX_RX[prt]_ADR_CTL[CAM_MODE] ? REJECT : ACCEPT);
01911  *      ]
01912  *      @endverbatim
01913  *
01914  * Additionally reset when MIX<prt>_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
01915  */
01916 union cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl {
01917     uint64_t u64;
01918     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s {
01919 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01920     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
01921     uint64_t cam_mode                     : 1;  /**< Allow or deny DMAC address filter
01922                                                          0 = reject the packet on DMAC address match
01923                                                          1 = accept the packet on DMAC address match */
01924     uint64_t mcst                         : 2;  /**< Multicast Mode
01925                                                          0 = Use the Address Filter CAM
01926                                                          1 = Force reject all multicast packets
01927                                                          2 = Force accept all multicast packets
01928                                                          3 = Reserved */
01929     uint64_t bcst                         : 1;  /**< Accept All Broadcast Packets */
01930 #else
01931     uint64_t bcst                         : 1;
01932     uint64_t mcst                         : 2;
01933     uint64_t cam_mode                     : 1;
01934     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
01935 #endif
01936     } s;
01937     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn52xx;
01938     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn52xxp1;
01939     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn56xx;
01940     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn56xxp1;
01941     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn61xx;
01942     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn63xx;
01943     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn63xxp1;
01944     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn66xx;
01945     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn68xx;
01946     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn68xxp1;
01947     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn70xx;
01948     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_s     cn70xxp1;
01949 };
01950 typedef union cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_adr_ctl_t;
01951 
01952 /**
01953  * cvmx_agl_gmx_rx#_decision
01954  *
01955  * AGL_GMX_RX_DECISION = The byte count to decide when to accept or filter a packet
01956  *
01957  *
01958  * Notes:
01959  * As each byte in a packet is received by GMX, the L2 byte count is compared
01960  * against the AGL_GMX_RX_DECISION[CNT].  The L2 byte count is the number of bytes
01961  * from the beginning of the L2 header (DMAC).  In normal operation, the L2
01962  * header begins after the PREAMBLE+SFD (AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK]=1) and any
01963  * optional UDD skip data (AGL_GMX_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN]).
01964  *
01965  * When AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] is clear, PREAMBLE+SFD are prepended to the
01966  * packet and would require UDD skip length to account for them.
01967  *
01968  *                                                 L2 Size
01969  * Port Mode             <=AGL_GMX_RX_DECISION bytes (default=24)  >AGL_GMX_RX_DECISION bytes (default=24)
01970  *
01971  * MII/Full Duplex       accept packet                             apply filters
01972  *                       no filtering is applied                   accept packet based on DMAC and PAUSE packet filters
01973  *
01974  * MII/Half Duplex       drop packet                               apply filters
01975  *                       packet is unconditionally dropped         accept packet based on DMAC
01976  *
01977  * where l2_size = MAX(0, total_packet_size - AGL_GMX_RX_UDD_SKP[LEN] - ((AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK]==1)*8)
01978  *
01979  * Additionally reset when MIX<prt>_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
01980  */
01981 union cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision {
01982     uint64_t u64;
01983     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s {
01984 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01985     uint64_t reserved_5_63                : 59;
01986     uint64_t cnt                          : 5;  /**< The byte count to decide when to accept or filter
01987                                                          a packet. */
01988 #else
01989     uint64_t cnt                          : 5;
01990     uint64_t reserved_5_63                : 59;
01991 #endif
01992     } s;
01993     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn52xx;
01994     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn52xxp1;
01995     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn56xx;
01996     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn56xxp1;
01997     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn61xx;
01998     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn63xx;
01999     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn63xxp1;
02000     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn66xx;
02001     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn68xx;
02002     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn68xxp1;
02003     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn70xx;
02004     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_s    cn70xxp1;
02005 };
02006 typedef union cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_decision_t;

02089 /**
02090  * cvmx_agl_gmx_rx#_frm_ctl
02091  *
02092  * AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CTL = Frame Control
02093  *
02094  *
02095  * Notes:
02096  * * PRE_STRP
02097  *   When PRE_CHK is set (indicating that the PREAMBLE will be sent), PRE_STRP
02098  *   determines if the PREAMBLE+SFD bytes are thrown away or sent to the Octane
02099  *   core as part of the packet.
02100  *
02101  *   In either mode, the PREAMBLE+SFD bytes are not counted toward the packet
02102  *   size when checking against the MIN and MAX bounds.  Furthermore, the bytes
02103  *   are skipped when locating the start of the L2 header for DMAC and Control
02104  *   frame recognition.
02105  *
02106  * * CTL_BCK/CTL_DRP
02107  *   These bits control how the HW handles incoming PAUSE packets.  Here are
02108  *   the most common modes of operation:
02109  *     CTL_BCK=1,CTL_DRP=1   - HW does it all
02110  *     CTL_BCK=0,CTL_DRP=0   - SW sees all pause frames
02111  *     CTL_BCK=0,CTL_DRP=1   - all pause frames are completely ignored
02112  *
02113  *   These control bits should be set to CTL_BCK=0,CTL_DRP=0 in halfdup mode.
02114  *   Since PAUSE packets only apply to fulldup operation, any PAUSE packet
02115  *   would constitute an exception which should be handled by the processing
02116  *   cores.  PAUSE packets should not be forwarded.
02117  *
02118  * Additionally reset when MIX<prt>_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
02119  */
02120 union cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_frm_ctl {
02121     uint64_t u64;
02122     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_frm_ctl_s {
02123 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02124     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
02125     uint64_t ptp_mode                     : 1;  /**< Timestamp mode
02126                                                          When PTP_MODE is set, a 64-bit timestamp will be
02127                                                          prepended to every incoming packet. The timestamp
02128                                                          bytes are added to the packet in such a way as to
02129                                                          not modify the packet's receive byte count.  This
02130                                                          implies that the AGL_GMX_RX_JABBER,
02131                                                          AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_MIN, AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_MAX,
02132                                                          AGL_GMX_RX_DECISION, AGL_GMX_RX_UDD_SKP, and the
02133                                                          AGL_GMX_RX_STATS_* do not require any adjustment
02134                                                          as they operate on the received packet size.
02135                                                          If PTP_MODE=1 and PRE_CHK=1, PRE_STRP must be 1. */
02136     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
02137     uint64_t null_dis                     : 1;  /**< When set, do not modify the MOD bits on NULL ticks
02138                                                          due to PARITAL packets */
02139     uint64_t pre_align                    : 1;  /**< When set, PREAMBLE parser aligns the the SFD byte
02140                                                          regardless of the number of previous PREAMBLE
02141                                                          nibbles.  In this mode, PRE_STRP should be set to
02142                                                          account for the variable nature of the PREAMBLE.
02143                                                          PRE_CHK must be set to enable this and all
02144                                                          PREAMBLE features. */
02145     uint64_t pad_len                      : 1;  /**< When set, disables the length check for non-min
02146                                                          sized pkts with padding in the client data */
02147     uint64_t vlan_len                     : 1;  /**< When set, disables the length check for VLAN pkts */
02148     uint64_t pre_free                     : 1;  /**< When set, PREAMBLE checking is less strict.
02149                                                          AGL will begin the frame at the first SFD.
02150                                                          PRE_FREE must be set if PRE_ALIGN is set.
02151                                                          PRE_CHK must be set to enable this and all
02152                                                          PREAMBLE features. */
02153     uint64_t ctl_smac                     : 1;  /**< Control Pause Frames can match station SMAC */
02154     uint64_t ctl_mcst                     : 1;  /**< Control Pause Frames can match globally assign
02155                                                          Multicast address */
02156     uint64_t ctl_bck                      : 1;  /**< Forward pause information to TX block */
02157     uint64_t ctl_drp                      : 1;  /**< Drop Control Pause Frames */
02158     uint64_t pre_strp                     : 1;  /**< Strip off the preamble (when present)
02159                                                          0=PREAMBLE+SFD is sent to core as part of frame
02160                                                          1=PREAMBLE+SFD is dropped
02161                                                          PRE_STRP must be set if PRE_ALIGN is set.
02162                                                          PRE_CHK must be set to enable this and all
02163                                                          PREAMBLE features. */
02164     uint64_t pre_chk                      : 1;  /**< This port is configured to send a valid 802.3
02165                                                          PREAMBLE to begin every frame. AGL checks that a
02166                                                          valid PREAMBLE is received (based on PRE_FREE).
02167                                                          When a problem does occur within the PREAMBLE
02168                                                          seqeunce, the frame is marked as bad and not sent
02169                                                          into the core.  The AGL_GMX_RX_INT_REG[PCTERR]
02170                                                          interrupt is also raised. */
02171 #else

02175     uint64_t ctl_bck                      : 1;

02192                                                          regardless of the number of previous PREAMBLE
02193                                                          nibbles.  In this mode, PREAMBLE can be consumed
02194                                                          by the HW so when PRE_ALIGN is set, PRE_FREE,

02215                                                          PRE_CHK must be set to enable this and all

02547 /**
02548  * cvmx_agl_gmx_rx#_int_reg
02549  *
02550  * AGL_GMX_RX_INT_REG = Interrupt Register
02551  *
02552  *
02553  * Notes:
02554  * (1) exceptions will only be raised to the control processor if the
02555  *     corresponding bit in the AGL_GMX_RX_INT_EN register is set.
02556  *
02557  * (2) exception conditions 10:0 can also set the rcv/opcode in the received
02558  *     packet's workQ entry.  The AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CHK register provides a bit mask
02559  *     for configuring which conditions set the error.
02560  *
02561  * (3) in half duplex operation, the expectation is that collisions will appear
02562  *     as MINERRs.
02563  *
02564  * (4) JABBER - An RX Jabber error indicates that a packet was received which
02565  *              is longer than the maximum allowed packet as defined by the
02566  *              system.  GMX will truncate the packet at the JABBER count.
02567  *              Failure to do so could lead to system instabilty.
02568  *
02569  * (6) MAXERR - for untagged frames, the total frame DA+SA+TL+DATA+PAD+FCS >
02570  *              AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_MAX.  For tagged frames, DA+SA+VLAN+TL+DATA+PAD+FCS
02571  *              > AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_MAX + 4*VLAN_VAL + 4*VLAN_STACKED.
02572  *
02573  * (7) MINERR - total frame DA+SA+TL+DATA+PAD+FCS < AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_MIN.
02574  *
02575  * (8) ALNERR - Indicates that the packet received was not an integer number of
02576  *              bytes.  If FCS checking is enabled, ALNERR will only assert if
02577  *              the FCS is bad.  If FCS checking is disabled, ALNERR will
02578  *              assert in all non-integer frame cases.
02579  *
02580  * (9) Collisions - Collisions can only occur in half-duplex mode.  A collision
02581  *                  is assumed by the receiver when the received
02582  *                  frame < AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_MIN - this is normally a MINERR
02583  *
02584  * (A) LENERR - Length errors occur when the received packet does not match the
02585  *              length field.  LENERR is only checked for packets between 64
02586  *              and 1500 bytes.  For untagged frames, the length must exact
02587  *              match.  For tagged frames the length or length+4 must match.
02588  *
02589  * (B) PCTERR - checks that the frame begins with a valid PREAMBLE sequence.
02590  *              Does not check the number of PREAMBLE cycles.
02591  *
02592  * (C) OVRERR -
02593  *
02594  *              OVRERR is an architectural assertion check internal to GMX to
02595  *              make sure no assumption was violated.  In a correctly operating
02596  *              system, this interrupt can never fire.
02597  *
02598  *              GMX has an internal arbiter which selects which of 4 ports to
02599  *              buffer in the main RX FIFO.  If we normally buffer 8 bytes,
02600  *              then each port will typically push a tick every 8 cycles - if
02601  *              the packet interface is going as fast as possible.  If there
02602  *              are four ports, they push every two cycles.  So that's the
02603  *              assumption.  That the inbound module will always be able to
02604  *              consume the tick before another is produced.  If that doesn't
02605  *              happen - that's when OVRERR will assert.
02606  *
02607  * Additionally reset when MIX<prt>_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
02608  */
02609 union cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_int_reg {
02610     uint64_t u64;

02638 #else

02771 /**
02772  * cvmx_agl_gmx_rx#_jabber
02773  *
02774  * AGL_GMX_RX_JABBER = The max size packet after which GMX will truncate
02775  *
02776  *
02777  * Notes:
02778  * CNT must be 8-byte aligned such that CNT[2:0] == 0
02779  *
02780  *   The packet that will be sent to the packet input logic will have an
02781  *   additionl 8 bytes if AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] is set and
02782  *   AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_STRP] is clear.  The max packet that will be sent is
02783  *   defined as...
02784  *
02785  *        max_sized_packet = AGL_GMX_RX_JABBER[CNT]+((AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] & !AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_STRP])*8)
02786  *
02787  *   Be sure the CNT field value is at least as large as the
02788  *   AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_MAX[LEN] value. Failure to meet this constraint will cause
02789  *   packets that are within the AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_MAX[LEN] length to be rejected
02790  *   because they exceed the CNT limit.
02791  *
02792  * Additionally reset when MIX<prt>_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
02793  */
02794 union cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber {
02795     uint64_t u64;
02796     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s {
02797 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02798     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
02799     uint64_t cnt                          : 16; /**< Byte count for jabber check
02800                                                          Failing packets set the JABBER interrupt and are
02801                                                          optionally sent with opcode==JABBER
02802                                                          GMX will truncate the packet to CNT bytes
02803                                                          CNT >= AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_MAX[LEN] */
02804 #else
02805     uint64_t cnt                          : 16;
02806     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
02807 #endif
02808     } s;
02809     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn52xx;
02810     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn52xxp1;
02811     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn56xx;
02812     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn56xxp1;
02813     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn61xx;
02814     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn63xx;
02815     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn63xxp1;
02816     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn66xx;
02817     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn68xx;
02818     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn68xxp1;
02819     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn70xx;
02820     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_jabber_s      cn70xxp1;
02821 };

03245 /**
03246  * cvmx_agl_gmx_rx#_udd_skp
03247  *
03248  * AGL_GMX_RX_UDD_SKP = Amount of User-defined data before the start of the L2 data
03249  *
03250  *
03251  * Notes:
03252  * (1) The skip bytes are part of the packet and will be sent down the NCB
03253  *     packet interface and will be handled by PKI.
03254  *
03255  * (2) The system can determine if the UDD bytes are included in the FCS check
03256  *     by using the FCSSEL field - if the FCS check is enabled.
03257  *
03258  * (3) Assume that the preamble/sfd is always at the start of the frame - even
03259  *     before UDD bytes.  In most cases, there will be no preamble in these
03260  *     cases since it will be MII to MII communication without a PHY
03261  *     involved.
03262  *
03263  * (4) We can still do address filtering and control packet filtering is the
03264  *     user desires.
03265  *
03266  * (5) UDD_SKP must be 0 in half-duplex operation unless
03267  *     AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] is clear.  If AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CTL[PRE_CHK] is set,
03268  *     then UDD_SKP will normally be 8.
03269  *
03270  * (6) In all cases, the UDD bytes will be sent down the packet interface as
03271  *     part of the packet.  The UDD bytes are never stripped from the actual
03272  *     packet.
03273  *
03274  * (7) If LEN != 0, then AGL_GMX_RX_FRM_CHK[LENERR] will be disabled and AGL_GMX_RX_INT_REG[LENERR] will be zero
03275  *
03276  * Additionally reset when MIX<prt>_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
03277  */
03278 union cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp {
03279     uint64_t u64;
03280     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s {
03281 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03282     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
03283     uint64_t fcssel                       : 1;  /**< Include the skip bytes in the FCS calculation
03284                                                          0 = all skip bytes are included in FCS
03285                                                          1 = the skip bytes are not included in FCS */
03286     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
03287     uint64_t len                          : 7;  /**< Amount of User-defined data before the start of
03288                                                          the L2 data.  Zero means L2 comes first.
03289                                                          Max value is 64. */
03290 #else
03291     uint64_t len                          : 7;
03292     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
03293     uint64_t fcssel                       : 1;
03294     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
03295 #endif
03296     } s;
03297     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn52xx;
03298     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn52xxp1;
03299     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn56xx;
03300     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn56xxp1;
03301     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn61xx;
03302     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn63xx;
03303     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn63xxp1;
03304     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn66xx;
03305     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn68xx;
03306     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn68xxp1;
03307     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn70xx;
03308     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_s     cn70xxp1;
03309 };
03310 typedef union cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp cvmx_agl_gmx_rxx_udd_skp_t;

03312 /**
03313  * cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_drop#
03314  *
03315  * AGL_GMX_RX_BP_DROP = FIFO mark for packet drop
03316  *
03317  *
03318  * Notes:
03319  * Additionally reset when MIX<prt>_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
03320  *
03321  */
03322 union cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx {
03323     uint64_t u64;
03324     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s {
03325 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03326     uint64_t reserved_6_63                : 58;
03327     uint64_t mark                         : 6;  /**< Number of 8B ticks to reserve in the RX FIFO.
03328                                                          When the FIFO exceeds this count, packets will
03329                                                          be dropped and not buffered.
03330                                                          MARK should typically be programmed to 2.
03331                                                          Failure to program correctly can lead to system
03332                                                          instability. */
03333 #else
03334     uint64_t mark                         : 6;
03335     uint64_t reserved_6_63                : 58;
03336 #endif
03337     } s;
03338     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn52xx;
03339     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn52xxp1;
03340     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn56xx;
03341     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn56xxp1;
03342     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn61xx;
03343     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn63xx;
03344     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn63xxp1;
03345     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn66xx;
03346     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn68xx;
03347     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn68xxp1;
03348     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_rx_bp_dropx_s     cn70xx;

03566 /**
03567  * cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp
03568  *
03569  * AGL_GMX_STAT_BP = Number of cycles that the TX/Stats block has help up operation
03570  *
03571  *
03572  * Notes:
03573  * Additionally reset when both MIX0/1_CTL[RESET] are set to 1.
03574  *
03575  *
03576  *
03577  * It has no relationship with the TX FIFO per se.  The TX engine sends packets
03578  * from PKO and upon completion, sends a command to the TX stats block for an
03579  * update based on the packet size.  The stats operation can take a few cycles -
03580  * normally not enough to be visible considering the 64B min packet size that is
03581  * ethernet convention.
03582  *
03583  * In the rare case in which SW attempted to schedule really, really, small packets
03584  * or the sclk (6xxx) is running ass-slow, then the stats updates may not happen in
03585  * real time and can back up the TX engine.
03586  *
03587  * This counter is the number of cycles in which the TX engine was stalled.  In
03588  * normal operation, it should always be zeros.
03589  */
03590 union cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp {
03591     uint64_t u64;
03592     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s {
03593 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03594     uint64_t reserved_17_63               : 47;
03595     uint64_t bp                           : 1;  /**< Current TX stats BP state
03596                                                          When the TX stats machine cannot update the stats
03597                                                          registers quickly enough, the machine has the
03598                                                          ability to BP TX datapath.  This is a rare event
03599                                                          and will not occur in normal operation.
03600                                                          0 = no backpressure is applied
03601                                                          1 = backpressure is applied to TX datapath to
03602                                                          allow stat update operations to complete */
03603     uint64_t cnt                          : 16; /**< Number of cycles that BP has been asserted
03604                                                          Saturating counter */
03605 #else
03606     uint64_t cnt                          : 16;
03607     uint64_t bp                           : 1;
03608     uint64_t reserved_17_63               : 47;
03609 #endif
03610     } s;
03611     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn52xx;
03612     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn52xxp1;
03613     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn56xx;
03614     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn56xxp1;
03615     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn61xx;
03616     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn63xx;
03617     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn63xxp1;
03618     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn66xx;
03619     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn68xx;
03620     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn68xxp1;
03621     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn70xx;
03622     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_s         cn70xxp1;
03623 };
03624 typedef union cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp cvmx_agl_gmx_stat_bp_t;

03653     uint64_t force_fcs                    : 1;
03654     uint64_t reserved_4_63                : 60;
03655 #endif
03656     } s;

03672 /**
03673  * cvmx_agl_gmx_tx#_clk
03674  *
03675  * AGL_GMX_TX_CLK = RGMII TX Clock Generation Register
03676  *
03677  *
03678  * Notes:
03679  * Normal Programming Values:
03680  *  (1) RGMII, 1000Mbs   (AGL_GMX_PRT_CFG[SPEED]==1), CLK_CNT == 1
03681  *  (2) RGMII, 10/100Mbs (AGL_GMX_PRT_CFG[SPEED]==0), CLK_CNT == 50/5
03682  *  (3) MII,   10/100Mbs (AGL_GMX_PRT_CFG[SPEED]==0), CLK_CNT == 1
03683  *
03684  * RGMII Example:
03685  *  Given a 125MHz PLL reference clock...
03686  *   CLK_CNT ==  1 ==> 125.0MHz TXC clock period (8ns* 1)
03687  *   CLK_CNT ==  5 ==>  25.0MHz TXC clock period (8ns* 5)
03688  *   CLK_CNT == 50 ==>   2.5MHz TXC clock period (8ns*50)
03689  *
03690  * Additionally reset when MIX<prt>_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
03691  */
03692 union cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk {
03693     uint64_t u64;
03694     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk_s {
03695 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03696     uint64_t reserved_6_63                : 58;
03697     uint64_t clk_cnt                      : 6;  /**< Controls the RGMII TXC frequency
03698                                                          TXC(period) =
03699                                                          rgm_ref_clk(period)*CLK_CNT */
03700 #else
03701     uint64_t clk_cnt                      : 6;
03702     uint64_t reserved_6_63                : 58;
03703 #endif
03704     } s;
03705     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk_s         cn61xx;
03706     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk_s         cn63xx;
03707     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk_s         cn63xxp1;
03708     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk_s         cn66xx;
03709     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk_s         cn68xx;
03710     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk_s         cn68xxp1;
03711     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk_s         cn70xx;
03712     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk_s         cn70xxp1;
03713 };
03714 typedef union cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_clk_t;

03796 /**
03797  * cvmx_agl_gmx_tx#_pause_pkt_interval
03798  *
03799  * AGL_GMX_TX_PAUSE_PKT_INTERVAL = Packet TX Pause Packet transmission interval - how often PAUSE packets will be sent
03800  *
03801  *
03802  * Notes:
03803  * Choosing proper values of AGL_GMX_TX_PAUSE_PKT_TIME[TIME] and
03804  * AGL_GMX_TX_PAUSE_PKT_INTERVAL[INTERVAL] can be challenging to the system
03805  * designer.  It is suggested that TIME be much greater than INTERVAL and
03806  * AGL_GMX_TX_PAUSE_ZERO[SEND] be set.  This allows a periodic refresh of the PAUSE
03807  * count and then when the backpressure condition is lifted, a PAUSE packet
03808  * with TIME==0 will be sent indicating that Octane is ready for additional
03809  * data.
03810  *
03811  * If the system chooses to not set AGL_GMX_TX_PAUSE_ZERO[SEND], then it is
03812  * suggested that TIME and INTERVAL are programmed such that they satisify the
03813  * following rule...
03814  *
03815  *    INTERVAL <= TIME - (largest_pkt_size + IFG + pause_pkt_size)
03816  *
03817  * where largest_pkt_size is that largest packet that the system can send
03818  * (normally 1518B), IFG is the interframe gap and pause_pkt_size is the size
03819  * of the PAUSE packet (normally 64B).
03820  *
03821  * Additionally reset when MIX<prt>_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
03822  */
03823 union cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval {
03824     uint64_t u64;
03825     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s {
03826 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03827     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
03828     uint64_t interval                     : 16; /**< Arbitrate for a pause packet every (INTERVAL*512)
03829                                                          bit-times.
03830                                                          Normally, 0 < INTERVAL < AGL_GMX_TX_PAUSE_PKT_TIME
03831                                                          INTERVAL=0, will only send a single PAUSE packet
03832                                                          for each backpressure event */
03833 #else
03834     uint64_t interval                     : 16;
03835     uint64_t reserved_16_63               : 48;
03836 #endif
03837     } s;
03838     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn52xx;
03839     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn52xxp1;
03840     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn56xx;
03841     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn56xxp1;
03842     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn61xx;
03843     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn63xx;
03844     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn63xxp1;
03845     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn66xx;
03846     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn68xx;
03847     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn68xxp1;
03848     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn70xx;
03849     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_s cn70xxp1;
03850 };
03851 typedef union cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval cvmx_agl_gmx_txx_pause_pkt_interval_t;
03852

04178 /**

04182  *
04183  *
04184  * Notes:
04185  * - Packet length is the sum of all data transmitted on the wire for the given
04186  *   packet including packet data, pad bytes, fcs bytes, pause bytes, and jam
04187  *   bytes.  The octect counts do not include PREAMBLE byte or EXTEND cycles.
04188  * - Cleared either by a write (of any value) or a read when AGL_GMX_TX_STATS_CTL[RD_CLR] is set
04189  * - Counters will wrap
04190  * - Not reset when MIX*_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.

04358  *   reality and should be ignored by software.

04367     uint64_t bcst                         : 32; /**< Number of packets sent to broadcast DMAC.
04368                                                          Does not include MCST packets. */
04369 #else
04370     uint64_t bcst                         : 32;
04371     uint64_t mcst                         : 32;
04372 #endif
04373     } s;

04589 /**
04590  * cvmx_agl_gmx_tx_ifg
04591  *
04592  * Common
04593  * AGL_GMX_TX_IFG = Packet TX Interframe Gap
04594  */
04595 union cvmx_agl_gmx_tx_ifg {
04596     uint64_t u64;
04597     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_tx_ifg_s {
04598 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04599     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
04600     uint64_t ifg2                         : 4;  /**< 1/3 of the interframe gap timing
04601                                                          If CRS is detected during IFG2, then the
04602                                                          interFrameSpacing timer is not reset and a frame
04603                                                          is transmited once the timer expires.
04604                                                          1000Mbs   = 4
04605                                                          10/100Mbs = 10
04606                                                          (In 10/100Mbs mode, total IFG doubled to 24 with
04607                                                          IFG2 increase to 10 for bug16930.)
04608                                                          (Bug16930 only applies to 6xxx series) */
04609     uint64_t ifg1                         : 4;  /**< 2/3 of the interframe gap timing
04610                                                          If CRS is detected during IFG1, then the
04611                                                          interFrameSpacing timer is reset and a frame is
04612                                                          not transmited.
04613                                                          1000Mbs   = 8
04614                                                          10/100Mbs = 14
04615                                                          (In 10/100Mbs mode, total IFG doubled to 24 with
04616                                                          IFG1 increase to 14 for bug16930.)
04617                                                          (Bug16930 only applies to 6xxx series) */
04618 #else
04619     uint64_t ifg1                         : 4;
04620     uint64_t ifg2                         : 4;
04621     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
04622 #endif
04623     } s;
04624     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_tx_ifg_s          cn52xx;
04625     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_tx_ifg_s          cn52xxp1;
04626     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_tx_ifg_s          cn56xx;
04627     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_tx_ifg_s          cn56xxp1;
04628     struct cvmx_agl_gmx_tx_ifg_s          cn61xx;

05146 /**
05147  * cvmx_agl_prt#_ctl
05148  *
05149  * AGL_PRT_CTL = AGL Port Control
05150  *
05151  *
05152  * Notes:
05153  * The RGMII timing specification requires that devices transmit clock and
05154  * data synchronously. The specification requires external sources (namely
05155  * the PC board trace routes) to introduce the appropriate 1.5 to 2.0 ns of
05156  * delay.
05157  *
05158  * To eliminate the need for the PC board delays, the MIX RGMII interface
05159  * has optional onboard DLL's for both transmit and receive. For correct
05160  * operation, at most one of the transmitter, board, or receiver involved
05161  * in an RGMII link should introduce delay. By default/reset,
05162  * the MIX RGMII receivers delay the received clock, and the MIX
05163  * RGMII transmitters do not delay the transmitted clock. Whether this
05164  * default works as-is with a given link partner depends on the behavior
05165  * of the link partner and the PC board.
05166  *
05167  * These are the possible modes of MIX RGMII receive operation:
05168  *  o AGL_PRTx_CTL[CLKRX_BYP] = 0 (reset value) - The OCTEON MIX RGMII
05169  *    receive interface introduces clock delay using its internal DLL.
05170  *    This mode is appropriate if neither the remote
05171  *    transmitter nor the PC board delays the clock.
05172  *  o AGL_PRTx_CTL[CLKRX_BYP] = 1, [CLKRX_SET] = 0x0 - The OCTEON MIX
05173  *    RGMII receive interface introduces no clock delay. This mode
05174  *    is appropriate if either the remote transmitter or the PC board
05175  *    delays the clock.
05176  *
05177  * These are the possible modes of MIX RGMII transmit operation:
05178  *  o AGL_PRTx_CTL[CLKTX_BYP] = 1, [CLKTX_SET] = 0x0 (reset value) -
05179  *    The OCTEON MIX RGMII transmit interface introduces no clock
05180  *    delay. This mode is appropriate is either the remote receiver
05181  *    or the PC board delays the clock.
05182  *  o AGL_PRTx_CTL[CLKTX_BYP] = 0 - The OCTEON MIX RGMII transmit
05183  *    interface introduces clock delay using its internal DLL.
05184  *    This mode is appropriate if neither the remote receiver
05185  *    nor the PC board delays the clock.
05186  *
05187  * AGL_PRT0_CTL will be reset when MIX0_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
05188  * AGL_PRT1_CTL will be reset when MIX1_CTL[RESET] is set to 1.
05189  */
05190 union cvmx_agl_prtx_ctl {
05191     uint64_t u64;
05192     struct cvmx_agl_prtx_ctl_s {
05193 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05194     uint64_t drv_byp                      : 1;  /**< When set, bypass the compensation controller and use
05195                                                          DRV_NCTL and DRV_PCTL */
05196     uint64_t reserved_62_62               : 1;
05197     uint64_t cmp_pctl                     : 6;  /**< PCTL drive strength from the HW compensation controller */
05198     uint64_t reserved_54_55               : 2;
05199     uint64_t cmp_nctl                     : 6;  /**< NCTL drive strength from the HW compensation controller */
05200     uint64_t reserved_46_47               : 2;
05201     uint64_t drv_pctl                     : 6;  /**< PCTL drive strength to use in bypass mode.
05202                                                          Reset value of 13 is for 50 ohm termination */
05203     uint64_t reserved_38_39               : 2;
05204     uint64_t drv_nctl                     : 6;  /**< NCTL drive strength to use in bypass mode.
05205                                                          Reset value of 12 is for 50 ohm termination */
05206     uint64_t reserved_31_31               : 1;
05207     uint64_t clk_set                      : 7;  /**< The clock delay as determined by the on board HW DLL */
05208     uint64_t clkrx_byp                    : 1;  /**< Bypass the RX clock delay setting
05209                                                          Skews RXC from RXD,RXCTL
05210                                                          By default, HW internally shifts the RXC clock
05211                                                          to sample RXD,RXCTL assuming clock and data and
05212                                                          sourced synchronously from the link partner. */
05213     uint64_t clkrx_set                    : 7;  /**< RX clock delay setting to use in bypass mode
05214                                                          Skews RXC from RXD */
05215     uint64_t clktx_byp                    : 1;  /**< Bypass the TX clock delay setting
05216                                                          Skews TXC from TXD,TXCTL
05217                                                          By default, clock and data and sourced
05218                                                          synchronously. */
05219     uint64_t clktx_set                    : 7;  /**< TX clock delay setting to use in bypass mode
05220                                                          Skews TXC from TXD */
05221     uint64_t refclk_sel                   : 2;  /**< Select the refclk to use.  Normal RGMII specification requires a 125MHz oscillator.  In
05222                                                          order to reduce system cost, a 500MHz coprocessor clock can be divided down and remove the
05223                                                          requirements for the external oscillator.  Additionally, in some well defined systems, the
05224                                                          link partner may be able to source the RXC.  The RGMII would operate correctly in 1000Mbs
05225                                                          mode only.  ( */
05226     uint64_t reserved_5_5                 : 1;
05227     uint64_t dllrst                       : 1;  /**< DLL Reset */
05228     uint64_t comp                         : 1;  /**< Compensation Enable */

05231     uint64_t mode                         : 1;  /**< Port Mode
05232                                                          0=RGMII */
05233 #else

05239     uint64_t reserved_5_5                 : 1;
05240     uint64_t refclk_sel                   : 2;
05241     uint64_t clktx_set                    : 7;

05243     uint64_t clkrx_set                    : 7;
